{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493292"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:04:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:04:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1278"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1278","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1278"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.79,0.06,0.04,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1278"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99936"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1278","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1278"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2019-11-30T10:07:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-23T11:56:00+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2023-01-05T17:58:56+10:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-27 17:45:44"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1278"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"12201"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82332"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"125"},{"type":"tags","id":"602"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1167"},{"type":"tags","id":"1654"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6051"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7907"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33746"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42275"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43069"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82332"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/99936"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a seven-day history of low back pain. The pain has worsened significantly in the last two days and is now disturbing her sleep. The pain does not radiate anywhere and she does not have any sensory disturbances, but she now finds it difficult to stand up. She takes regular paracetamol but it has not helped. Her bladder and bowel function are intact.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer medical history includes rheumatoid arthritis, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and hypertension. Her regular medications are tiotropium, fluticasone/eformoterol and perindopril/indapamide. Last month she had a one-week course of corticosteroids for a flare-up of her rheumatoid arthritis. Six months ago she had a ureteric stone removed. She tried intravenous recreational drugs when she was a teenager, but that lasted less than a year.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable with vital signs within normal limits. She has localised tenderness over the mid-lumbar spine.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most suggestive of the need for further investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Recent history of ureteric stone","New-onset weakness of her legs","Short course of oral corticosteroids","Intravenous drug use in her youth","History of rheumatoid arthritis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most worrying aspect of her history is the \u003Cstrong\u003Enew-onset weakness of her legs\u003C/strong\u003E which is suggestive of peripheral nerve involvement (radiculopathy) or possible spinal cord compression. Back pain together with neurological symptoms such as weakness requires urgent further investigation, with MRI being the preferred imaging modality. This is especially pertinent where there is rapid progression of symptoms or neurological compromise. Cauda equina syndrome is a surgical emergency and should be suspected where there is saddle anaesthesia or compromise of bowel or bladder function.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Erecent history of a ureteric stone\u003C/strong\u003E is not an indication for further assessment of back pain in this context. It is unlikely that her current back pain is due to ureteric colic, as ureteric colic commonly presents as an acute, severe back pain radiating to the groin. If ureteric colic were suspected, CT-KUB (non-contrast) would be the appropriate investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eshort course of oral corticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E is not an indication for further imaging. It is prolonged/sustained use of oral corticosteroids that predisposes users to osteoporosis and fragility fractures. Therefore, history of prolonged use of corticosteroids would be a red flag for back pain requiring further investigations, but a short course is not concerning.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous drug use in her youth\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most relevant history in this case. While IV drug use is a known \u0027red flag\u0027 for back pain as it increases the risk of spinal infection, it is unlikely for her to suffer from spinal infection due to IV drug use when she has stopped taking recreational drugs for more than 40 years.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ehistory of rheumatoid arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E alone is not a specific red flag for acute back pain, though cervical spine involvement can occur in rheumatoid disease. While rheumatoid arthritis can affect the spine, the new-onset weakness is a much more concerning feature requiring urgent investigation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Neurological symptoms are a \u0022red flag\u0022 in patients with low back pain requiring urgent investigation.","MRI is the preferred imaging modality for back pain with associated neurological symptoms.","Progressive weakness in the legs with back pain may indicate spinal cord compression requiring urgent assessment."],"references":["Waljee AK, Rogers MA, Lin P, Singal AG, Stein JD, Marks RM, Ayanian JZ, Nallamothu BK. Short term use of oral corticosteroids and related harms among adults in the United States: population based cohort study. Bmj. 2017 Apr 12;357. Available at: https://www.bmj.com/content/357/bmj.j1415","Chuo CY, Fu YC, Lu YM, Chen JC, Shen WJ, Yang CH, Chen CY. Spinal infection in intravenous drug abusers. Clinical Spine Surgery. 2007 Jun 1;20(4):324-8. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17538358/","Parr A, Askin G. Non-radicular low back pain: Assessment and evidence-based treatment. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2020 Nov;49(11):724-7. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2020/november/non-radicular-low-back-pain"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82332"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1278"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82332","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82332"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-23T11:54:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-23T11:56:24+09:30","number":11,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-04-23T11:55:59+09:30","plagiarismScore":0,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-1278-11.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250928%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_requ